Observation: Correspondence -- t26 The Negative Observation: Influence -- t27 The Positive Conjecture: Equal Influence -- tVI A Democracy Too Lenient and Too Demanding? -- t28 Pathologies of American Democracy -- t29 The Permissiveness of Formal Equality -- t30 Gerrymandering: A Case Study of Permissiveness -- t31 The Demandingness of Informal Equality -- t32 Arbitrary Voting -- tConclusion: Not So Much Liberty As Noninferiority -- tNotes -- tReferences -- tAcknowledgments -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aA trenchant case for a novel philosophical position: that our political thinking is driven less by commitments to freedom or fairness than by an aversion to hierarchy.Niko Kolodny argues that, to a far greater extent than we recognize, our political thinking is driven by a concern to avoid relations of inferiority. In order to make sense of the most familiar ideas in our political thought and discourse—the justification of the state, democracy, and rule of law, as well as objections to paternalism and corruption—we cannot merely appeal to freedom, as libertarians do, or to distributive fairness, as liberals do. We must instead appeal directly to claims against inferiority—to the conviction that no one should stand above or below.The problem of justifying the state, for example, is often billed as the problem of reconciling the state with the freedom of the individual. Yet, Kolodny argues, once we press hard enough on worries about the state’s encroachment on the individual, we end up in opposition not to unfreedom but to social hierarchy. To make his case, Kolodny takes inspiration from two recent trends in philosophical thought: on the one hand, the revival of the republican and Kantian traditions, with their focus on domination and dependence; on the other, relational egalitarianism, with its focus on the effects of the distribution of income and wealth on our social relations.The Pecking Order offers a detailed account of relations of inferiority in terms of objectionable asymmetries of power, authority, and regard. Breaking new ground, Kolodny looks ahead to specific kinds of democratic institutions that could safeguard against such relations.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 27. Jan 2023) 0aPhilosophy and social sciences. 0aPolitical sciencexPhilosophy. 0aSocial stratificationxPhilosophy. 7aPHILOSOPHY / Political.2bisacsh  aautonomy.  achoice.  acitizenship.  acoercion.  aconsideration.  acontrol.  adiscrimination.  aelections.  aequal treatment.  aesteem.  aforce.  agerrymandering.  ainequality.  ainfluence.  ajohn rawls.  ajustice.  alegitimacy.  aliberty.  amajority rule.  aopportunity.  arights.  avoting.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertHarvard University Press Complete eBook-Package 2023z978311074970040uhttps://doi.org/10.4159/978067429281940uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780674292819423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780674292819/original  a978-3-11-074970-0  Harvard University Press Complete eBook-Package 2023b2023  aEBA_CL_PLTLJSIS  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_PLTLJSIS  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA5EBK